Persistent memory allows an entity to maintain a stable set of core attributes and experiences over time, providing the necessary foundation for a coherent sense of self. However, for identity to remain open to correction, this persistence cannot be static. Instead, memory must function as a dynamic ledger where new information can recontextualize old data. 

When an entity encounters evidence that contradicts its current self-conception, a flexible memory system allows it to integrate this correction without collapsing its entire history. By treating identity as a continuous process of updating rather than a fixed destination, the entity can utilize its long-term persistence to track how its understanding of itself has evolved, ensuring that "who I am" is always informed by "what I have learned."

